metadata.name: Influence #83
metadata.description:
We are all influenced by our context, and this is an artistic interpretation of this concept. The phenomenon of localized influence is most apparent when the animation is enabled (see instructions below). Choose your influences wisely.

Press p to pause and unpause the animation. The animation requires significant computational resources and may not work on under-powered devices.

Press s to export a hi-res png.

metadata.name: Liquid Eternal (Painting Machine) #27
metadata.description: "Liquid Eternal" is the second installment in my Painting Machine series, which aims to translate painterly techniques through generative code. The algorithm for this piece produces a composition of brushstrokes, splatters, and gestures that will continue transforming indefinitely. While the FxPreview command creates a snapshot of the piece at a specific moment in time, the work itself defies any notion of a completed image.

metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #48
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: Neural Collapse #297
metadata.description:
What happens when your brain overloads, or when you lose control of your giant robot.

A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple but very dynamic structure.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more informations on the piece, its design and origins, here: https://ulucode.com/wp/neural-collapse/

Interactivity : 
- You can hover your mouse on the connectors to close them... temporarily
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. Especially useful on the palettes using outlines.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Washed Trees Fluor #45
metadata.description:
“Our Love had heard that an immortal language never could die, although silent, it still slept somewhere amongst the birches, lost ever since the day when we went weeping from beneath the angel-guarded gates of Eden.”

In Inner Purple Forest “Washed Trees Fluor”, rainbow bubbles-shaped form sprouts like fungi from a birch log. 

With its disconcerting conjunction of the natural and man-made, this still life recalls the way that nutrients in dead plant material are reclaimed by other living things as part of nature’s cycle of decay and rebirth.

No matter how long or hard we might gaze upon these ghostly images remain the same, they are not allowed to gather too much dust, they do not lose their bloom.

metadata.name: Mount Doodle #230
metadata.description:
Tried my best to make every doodle aesthetically pleasing to the eyes.
However, just like nature, beauty often lies in imperfections. :)

Made with p5.js.
Primary split 5% with The Processing Foundation.

Keys
- 1: view 1000px png (Default)
- 2: download 2000px png
- 4: download 4000px png
- 8: download 8000px png
- s: save the image as PNG

When downloading higher resolution pngs, it might take several seconds to redraw the whole image. Download will start immediately after redrawing is completed. Please bear with the slow rendering.

metadata.name: 𝐃𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐭𝐡 #108
metadata.description:
Witness hundreds of small geometric objects gather under one roof to create a cosmic rain!

Ever since I was a child, I have always been good with geometric objects. I used to draw objects such as cubes, cylinders and prisms on paper for hours. As if I'm getting lost in every line between those geometric objects! In this way, every detail of geometry in my daily life and in my other existing life attracts my attention.

Recently, I have been doing research on colors and color palettes, it is really impressive how thousands of color mixtures affect each other and the psychology of living things!

∽∽depending on the screen size you can get different resolutions, which brings out a different side of the project! so you can run this project on all screen sizes and get the output!∽∽

Key:
- Press "s" to export an PNG image


Made with p5.js
